  // -- FAQ --
  faq: [
    { question: 'What types of school worksheets can I create?', answer: 'You can generate school-themed coloring pages, matching activities for supplies and functions, find-and-count classroom scenes, grid-match visual puzzles, addition and subtraction with school contexts, alphabet train activities with school vocabulary, handwriting practice with school words, word searches featuring classroom terminology, sudoku with school-supply symbols, odd-one-out analytical puzzles, and pattern worksheets with school-day sequences.' },
    { question: 'Are the school worksheets free?', answer: 'Yes, all school-themed worksheets on LessonCraftStudio are free to create and download. Choose the worksheet type, select the school theme, adjust settings to your preferred difficulty level, and generate a printable PDF for classroom or home use.' },
    { question: 'When is the best time to use school worksheets?', answer: 'School worksheets are valuable year-round but especially useful during three key periods: before school starts to build familiarity and reduce anxiety, during the first weeks to reinforce routines and vocabulary, and during transitions like moving to a new grade or school. They also work well as back-to-school review activities after winter or summer breaks.' },
    { question: 'How do school worksheets support social-emotional learning?', answer: 'School-themed activities naturally address social-emotional skills by depicting classroom social situations, cooperation scenarios, and emotional management contexts. Worksheets about sharing supplies teach generosity, activities about classroom rules teach self-regulation, and puzzles that require persistence teach frustration tolerance. The school theme makes social-emotional learning concrete rather than abstract.' },
    { question: 'Can school worksheets help a child who dislikes school?', answer: 'Yes. Completing enjoyable school-themed activities like puzzles and coloring pages at home builds a positive association with school-related content. When a child sees school imagery connected to the pleasure of solving a puzzle or creating artwork, their overall emotional response to school concepts becomes more positive over time. This is especially effective when paired with encouraging conversation about school experiences.' },
    { question: 'What classroom vocabulary do the worksheets teach?', answer: 'School worksheets feature vocabulary including school supplies like pencil, eraser, ruler, scissors, and glue, classroom areas like desk, board, library, and playground, school roles like teacher, student, and principal, daily events like recess, lunch, and homework, and academic subjects like reading, math, art, and science. Word searches and writing activities are particularly effective for building this vocabulary.' },
    { question: 'How do school worksheets differ from back-to-school worksheets?', answer: 'Our school worksheets are designed for use throughout the entire school year, not just the first week. While they are excellent for back-to-school transitions, they also serve as ongoing tools for reinforcing classroom skills, practicing academic content in familiar contexts, and developing the meta-learning skills that support all academic work regardless of the time of year.' },
    { question: 'Are school worksheets appropriate for homeschool families?', answer: 'Yes. Homeschool families can use school worksheets to introduce classroom concepts and vocabulary that homeschooled children might encounter in co-ops, community classes, or standardized testing. The worksheets also help homeschool parents create structured learning routines that mirror classroom practices, providing children with the experience of following directions and completing independent assignments.' },
    { question: 'How do puzzle-based school worksheets build learning skills?', answer: 'Sudoku, odd-one-out, and pattern worksheets develop the executive function skills that underpin all academic learning: sustained attention, logical reasoning, flexible thinking, and persistence through difficulty. When these puzzles use school-themed content, they simultaneously build familiarity with the school environment, making them doubly productive as both cognitive training and school readiness activities.' },
    { question: 'Can school worksheets be used for assessment purposes?', answer: 'Teachers can use school-themed worksheets as informal formative assessments. A find-and-count worksheet reveals whether a child can count accurately in a visually busy scene. A matching worksheet shows whether a child understands school supply functions. A word search indicates letter recognition and visual scanning ability. Because the school theme is familiar and low-stakes, children perform more naturally than on formal assessments, giving teachers a more accurate picture of actual abilities.' },
  ],

